  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Providing IDP camps with solar power and stoves as alternative energy sources</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">- At least 90% of IDP households have access to and use solar power and stoves at least 3 times a week.  
- At least 20% of households are exposed to improved livelihood opportunities through trading of rice husk and saw dust and adopt climate-friendly cooking alternatives.
- At least 50% of IDP households are innovating with solar ovens and using them for purposes other than as part of cooking for the family. 
- 80% of the households have reduced the amount of firewood and fossil fuel used for cooking in at least 50% in relation to the base line. 
- 80% of the households have reduced the amount of money spent on fossil fuel for cooking by 50% in relation to the base line. 
- Women and men that prepare food with the stoves have reduced their exposure to carbon monoxide and suspended airborne particulates (2.5 particulate matter) by 50%. 
- In at least 50% of the IDPs camps where women have been trained, they are actively participating in community planning processes and decisions</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Purchase and installation of solar plants and stoves, capacity building and technical assistance, participant exchange visits, communication and visibility, advocacy visits, behaviour change communication, base line studies and academic research</narrative>
  </description>
